title: Interlacing triangles, Schubert puzzles, and graph colorings

sections.text:
#### Abstract

We show that interlacing triangular arrays, introduced by Aggarwal-Borodin-Wheeler to study certain probability measures, can be used to compute structure constants for multiplying Schubert classes in the $K$-theory of Grassmannians, in the cohomology of their cotangent bundles, and in the cohomology of partial flag varieties. Our results are achieved by establishing a splitting lemma, allowing for interlacing triangular arrays of high rank to be decomposed into arrays of lower rank, and by constructing a bijection between interlacing triangular arrays of rank 3 with certain proper vertex colorings of the triangular grid graph that factors through generalizations of Knutson-Tao puzzles. Along the way, we prove one enumerative conjecture of Aggarwal-Borodin-Wheeler and disprove another.

## 1. INTRODUCTION

The LLT polynomials are a 1-parameter family of symmetric polynomials introduced by Lascoux, Leclerc, and Thibon [17]. They have close connections to Macdonald polynomials [8, 9] and Kazhdan-Lusztig theory [7], among other areas of representation theory and geometry.

In recent work, Aggarwal, Borodin, and Wheeler [1] studied probability measures arising from the Cauchy identity for LLT polynomials. They show that these measures asymptotically split into a continuous part, given by a product of GUE corners processes, and a discrete part, supported on interlacing triangular arrays. They conjectured that these arrays are equinumerous with vertex colorings of the triangular grid graph in the "rank-3" case, and with vertex colorings of another grid graph in the rank- 4 case. We construct a bijection between interlacing arrays and vertex colorings proving the first conjecture, and we disprove the second.

Our bijection factors through intermediate objects which are certain edge labelings of the triangular grid graph. We recognize these edge labelings as cryptomorphic to certain Schubert calculus puzzles [12, 13]. We apply various geometric interpretations of puzzles $[10,15,19,20]$ to prove that the corresponding families of interlacing triangular arrays compute structure constants in cohomology $H^{*}(\operatorname{Gr}(d, n))$ and $K$-theory $K(\operatorname{Gr}(d, n))$ of Grassmannians, in the (localized) cohomology $H_{\mathrm{C}^{\mathrm{clc}}}^{\mathrm{cloc}}\left(T^{*} \mathrm{Gr}(d, n)\right)$ of their cotangent bundles, and for the multiplication in the cohomology of partial flag varieties of classes pulled back from smaller partial flag varieties.

1.1. Interlacing triangular arrays and graph colorings. Let $[m]:=\{1, \ldots, m\}$. For integers $m, n \geq 1$ and tuples $\lambda^{(i)} \in[m]^{n}$ for $i=1, \ldots, m$, we write $\mathcal{T}_{m, n}\left(\lambda^{(1)}, \ldots, \lambda^{(m)}\right)$ for the set of interlacing triangular arrays of rank $m$ and height $n$ with top row $\lambda^{(1)}, \ldots, \lambda^{(m)}$ (see Section 2.1). We write $\mathcal{T}_{m, n}$ for $\bigsqcup_{\lambda} \mathcal{T}_{m, n}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$.
Conjecture 1.1 (Conj. A. 3 of Aggarwal-Borodin-Wheeler [1]). For $n \geq 1$, we have

$$
\left|\mathcal{T}_{3, n}\right|=\frac{1}{4}\left|\left\{\text { proper vertex } 4 \text {-colorings of } \Delta_{n}\right\}\right|
$$

where $\Delta_{n}$ denotes the equilateral triangular grid graph with $n$ edges on each side.
Our first main theorem resolves and significantly refines and extends Conjecture 1.1.

Theorem 1.2. Let $n \geq 1$ and fix $\lambda^{(1)}, \lambda^{(2)}, \lambda^{(3)} \in[3]^{n}$. Then the following sets of objects are in bijection:
(1) Interlacing triangular arrays $\mathcal{T}_{3, n}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ of rank 3 with top row $\boldsymbol{\lambda}$;
(2) $1 / 2 / 3$-puzzles $\mathcal{P}_{n}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ with boundary conditions $\boldsymbol{\lambda}$;
(3) $0 / 1 / 10$-puzzles $\widetilde{\mathcal{P}}_{n}(\boldsymbol{\xi})$ with boundary conditions $\boldsymbol{\xi}=\operatorname{str}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$;
(4) Proper vertex 4-colorings $\mathcal{C}_{n}(\boldsymbol{\kappa})$ of $\Delta_{n}$ with boundary colors $\boldsymbol{\kappa}=\operatorname{col}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$.

The functions str, col, and top are conversions between the different kinds of indexing data; their definitions can be found in Sections 4.1 and 5.1. To avoid confusion, throughout the paper we draw interlacing triangular arrays in green $(\square), 1 / 2 / 3$ puzzles in blue $(\square), 0 / 1 / 10$-puzzles in cyan $(\square)$, and vertex-colored graphs in red $(\square)$.

The colorings $\bigsqcup_{\boldsymbol{\kappa}=\operatorname{col}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})} \mathcal{C}_{n}(\boldsymbol{\kappa})$ from Theorem 1.2(4) are exactly those proper vertex 4 -colorings of $\Delta_{n}$ in which the base vertex is colored with the first color. The number of these is one fourth the total number of proper vertex 4 -colorings, so Theorem 1.2 implies Conjecture 1.1.

The particular bijections underlying Theorem 1.2 allow us to give geometric interpretations for certain sets of interlacing triangular arrays (see Section 1.2).

Aggarwal, Borodin, and Wheeler also conjectured a connection between interlacing triangular arrays of rank 4 and graph colorings. Let $\boxtimes_{n}$ be the graph obtained from the $n \times n$ square grid graph $\square_{n}$ by adding the two diagonal edges of each face of $\square_{n}$.

Conjecture 1.3 (Conj. A. 5 of Aggarwal-Borodin-Wheeler [1]). For $n \geq 1$, we have

$$
\left|\mathcal{T}_{4, n}\right|=\frac{1}{5}\left|\left\{\text { proper vertex } 5 \text {-colorings of } \boxtimes_{n}\right\}\right|
$$

In Theorem 1.4 we give a bijection between interlacing triangular arrays of rank 4 and certain edge labelings of the square grid graph $\square_{n}$, which are analogous to the $1 / 2 / 3$-puzzles of Theorem $1.2(2)$.

Theorem 1.4. Let $n \geq 1$ and fix $\lambda^{(1)}, \lambda^{(2)}, \lambda^{(3)}, \lambda^{(4)} \in[4]^{n}$. Then the following sets of objects are in bijection:
(1) Interlacing triangular arrays $\mathcal{T}_{4, n}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ of rank 4 with top row $\boldsymbol{\lambda}$;
(2) Edge labelings $\mathcal{D}_{n}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ of the square grid graph $\square_{n}$ having boundary conditions $\boldsymbol{\lambda}$ and satisfying the conditions of Section 4.2.

Unlike in the rank-3 case, there is no straightforward way to biject the objects in Theorem 1.4 with proper vertex colorings. In particular, by enumerating $\mathcal{D}_{4}$ we show that Conjecture 1.3 is false ${ }^{1}$, as

$$
\left|\mathcal{T}_{4,4}\right|=191232 \neq 187008=\frac{1}{5}\left|\left\{\text { proper vertex } 5 \text {-colorings of } \boxtimes_{4}\right\}\right|
$$

1.2. Geometric interpretations of interlacing triangular arrays. The $0 / 1 / 10$ puzzles appearing in Theorem $1.2(3)$ are known to have various geometric interpretations when certain puzzle pieces are forbidden and when the boundary conditions are taken appropriately. The number of such puzzles with boundary conditions $\boldsymbol{\xi}=\left(\xi^{(1)}, \xi^{(2)}, \xi^{(3)}\right)$ computes the coefficient of the basis element indexed by $\xi^{(3)}$ in the product of basis elements indexed by $\xi^{(1)}$ and $\xi^{(2)}$ in cohomology $H^{*}(\operatorname{Gr}(d, n))$ and $K$-theory $K(\operatorname{Gr}(d, n))$ of Grassmannians, in the (appropriately localized) cohomology $H_{\xi / s}^{\text {sloc }}\left(T^{*} \operatorname{Gr}(d, n)\right)$ of their cotangent bundles, and for the multiplication in the cohomology of the 2 -step flag variety $[13,15,19,20]$.

We use the specific bijections underlying Theorem 1.2 to show that interlacing triangular arrays with forbidden patterns and specified top row likewise compute these coefficients. One advantage of interlacing triangular arrays is that they allow for an interpretation of coefficients in the expansion of an $(m-1)$-fold product, without the need to iteratively apply a rule for products of two elements.

For $\xi$ a 0,1 -string with content $0^{d} 1^{n-d}$, let $G_{\xi}$ denote the class of the structure sheaf of the Schubert variety $X_{\xi} \subset \operatorname{Gr}(d, n)$ inside $K(\operatorname{Gr}(d, n))$. These classes can be represented by the (Grassmannian) Grothendieck polynomials. The $\left\{G_{\xi}\right\}$ form a basis for $K(\operatorname{Gr}(d, n))$. In Theorem 1.5 we show that the structure constants for multiplication in the basis $\left\{G_{\xi}\right\}$ are equal (up to signs) to the number of certain interlacing triangular arrays. Even the positivity of these structure constants (up to predictable signs, based on degree) is not obvious, and is due originally to Buch $[3]$.

Given a tuple $\boldsymbol{\xi}=\left(\xi^{(1)}, \ldots, \xi^{(m)}\right)$ of 0,1 -strings, define $|\boldsymbol{\xi}|=\sum_{i}\left|\xi^{(i)}\right|$, where $\left|\xi^{(i)}\right|$ is the number of inversions of $\xi^{(i)}$. For $\xi$ of content $0^{d} 1^{n-d}$, we denote by $\xi^{\perp}$ the reversed string.
Theorem 1.5. Let $\xi^{(1)}, \ldots, \xi^{(m)}$ have content $0^{d} 1^{n-d}$. Let coefficients $g_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}=g_{\xi^{(1)}, \ldots, \xi^{(m)}}$ be determined by

$$
\prod_{i=1}^{m-1} G_{\xi^{(i)}}=\sum_{\xi^{(m)}} g_{\boldsymbol{\xi}} G_{\left(\xi^{(m)}\right)^{\perp}}
$$

Then $(-1)^{d(n-d)-|\xi|} g_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}$ is the number of interlacing triangular arrays $T$ from $\mathcal{T}_{m, n}(\operatorname{top}(\boldsymbol{\xi}))$ such that, for $i=2, \ldots, m-1, T^{(i)}$ avoids

$$
m-i \quad \text { and } \quad m-i+i-m
$$

Dual to $\left\{G_{\xi}\right\}$ is the basis $\left\{G_{\xi}^{*}\right\}$ of ideal sheaves: functions on Schubert varieties vanishing on smaller Schubert varieties. The $G_{\xi}^{*}$ can be represented by dual Grothendieck polynomials.
Theorem 1.6. Let $\xi^{(1)}, \ldots, \xi^{(m)}$ have content $0^{d} 1^{n-d}$. Let coefficients $g_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}^{*}=g_{\xi^{(1)}, \ldots, \xi^{(m)}}^{*}$ be determined by

$$
\prod_{i=1}^{m-1} G_{\xi^{(i)}}^{*}=\sum_{\xi^{(m)}} g_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}^{*} G_{\left(\xi^{(m)}\right)^{\perp}}^{*}
$$

Then $(-1)^{d(n-d)-|\xi|} g_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}^{*}$ is the number of interlacing triangular arrays $T$ from $\mathcal{T}_{m, n}(\operatorname{top}(\boldsymbol{\xi}))$ such that, for $i=2, \ldots, m-1, T^{(i)}$ avoids

$$
m-i \quad \text { and } \quad m-i+i
$$

Interlacing triangular arrays avoiding both the patterns (2) and (3) compute structure constants in the ordinary cohomology of the Grassmannian. In fact, in this case we can generalize to products of certain classes in the cohomology of arbitrary partial flag varieties.

For $\boldsymbol{d}=\left(0=d_{0} \leq d_{1} \leq \cdots \leq d_{m}=n\right)$, let $\mathrm{Fl}(\boldsymbol{d} ; n)$ denote the partial flag variety of flags of subspaces of $\mathbb{C}^{n}$ with dimension vector $\boldsymbol{d}$. Let $S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}}$ denote the set of permutations whose descents are contained in $\boldsymbol{d}$. Then $H^{*}(\mathrm{Fl}(\boldsymbol{d} ; n))$ has a basis $\left\{\sigma_{w}\right\}_{w \in S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}}}$ consisting of the classes of the Schubert varieties in $\mathrm{Fl}(\boldsymbol{d} ; n)$ (see Section 2.2). In particular, the class $\sigma_{w_{0}^{\boldsymbol{d}}}$ of the longest element of $S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}}$ is the class of a point. For $w^{(1)}, \ldots, w^{(m)} \in S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}}$, let coefficients $c_{\boldsymbol{w}}=c_{w^{(1)}, \ldots, w^{(m)}}$ be determined by

$$
\prod_{i=1}^{m-1} \sigma_{w^{(i)}}=\sum_{w^{(m)}} c_{\boldsymbol{w}} \sigma_{\left(w^{(m)}\right)^{\vee} \boldsymbol{d}}
$$

where $w^{\vee \boldsymbol{d}}:=w_{0} w w_{0}(\boldsymbol{d})$.

Theorem 1.7. Let $\boldsymbol{d}=\left(0=d_{0} \leq d_{1} \leq \cdots \leq d_{m}=n\right)$. For $i \in[m]$ let $\Sigma_{i}=$ $\{m-i<m<m-i+1\}$, let $\lambda^{(i)}$ be a string of type $(m-i)^{d_{m-i}} m^{d_{m-i+1}-d_{m-i}}(m-$ $i+1)^{n-d_{m-i+1}}$, and let $w^{(i)}=w\left(\lambda^{(i)}\right)_{\Sigma_{i}} \in S_{n}^{d}$ be the corresponding permutation (see Definition 2.5). Then $c_{w}$ is the number of interlacing triangular arrays $T$ from $\mathcal{T}_{m, n}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ such that, for $i=2, \ldots, m-1, T^{(i)}$ avoids the patterns from (2) and (3).

The Schubert classes $\sigma_{w^{(i)}}$ appearing in Theorem 1.7 are the pullbacks of Schubert classes under the projection from $\mathrm{Fl}(\boldsymbol{d} ; n)$ to certain 2 -step flag varieties. It is not clear how one might hope to extend Theorem 1.7 to provide rules for products of more general Schubert classes; combinatorial rules for products of arbitrary Schubert classes are known only for flag varieties with $m \leq 4$ steps (see, e.g. $[4,14,15]$ ).

Finally, let $H_{\mathbb{C}^{\times}}^{\text {sloc }}\left(T^{*} \operatorname{Gr}(d, n)\right)$ denote the equivariant cohomology of the cotangent bundle of $\operatorname{Gr}(d, n)$ with respect to the $\mathbb{C}^{\times}$-action scaling the cotangent spaces, localized as in $[15, \S 2.2]$. For $\xi$ of content $0^{d} 1^{n-d}$, let $S_{\xi} \in H_{\mathbb{C}^{\times}}^{\text {sloc }}\left(T^{*} \operatorname{Gr}(d, n)\right)$ denote the Segre-Schwartz-MacPherson (SSM) class of the corresponding Schubert variety, using the conventions of $[15, \S 2.4 \& \S 5.2]$ (see also $[5,18]$ ). In our last main theorem, we show that interlacing triangular arrays, with no forbidden patterns, compute structure constants for the $\left\{S_{\xi}\right\}$.

Theorem 1.8. Let $\xi^{(1)}, \ldots, \xi^{(m)}$ have content $0^{d} 1^{n-d}$. Let coefficients $s_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}=s_{\xi^{(1)}, \ldots, \xi^{(m)}}$ be determined by

$$
\prod_{i=1}^{m-1} S_{\xi^{(i)}}=\sum_{\xi^{(m)}} s_{\boldsymbol{\xi}} S_{\left(\xi^{(m)}\right) \perp}
$$

Then $(-1)^{d(n-d)-|\boldsymbol{\xi}|} s_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}$ is the cardinality of $\mathcal{T}_{m, n}(\operatorname{top}(\boldsymbol{\xi}))$.

1.4. Outline. In Section 2 we give background and definitions for interlacing triangular arrays and for partial flag varieties. In Section 3, we prove Theorem 3.5, establishing bijections

$$
\mathcal{T}_{3, n} \stackrel{\mathscr{T}}{\mathscr{S}} \mathcal{P}_{n}
$$

between rank-3 interlacing triangular arrays and $1 / 2 / 3$-puzzles. In Section 4 we in turn prove Theorem 4.2, giving bijections

$$
\mathcal{P}_{n} \stackrel{\mathscr{C}}{\mathscr{S}} \mathcal{C}_{n}
$$

between $1 / 2 / 3$-puzzles and proper vertex colorings of $\Delta_{n}$. In Theorem 4.4 we also give bijections

$$
\mathcal{T}_{4, n} \stackrel{\mathscr{D}}{\rightleftharpoons} \mathcal{D}_{n}
$$

between rank-4 interlacing triangular arrays and certain edge labelings of $\square_{n}$.
In Section 5, we show how to convert between $1 / 2 / 3$-puzzles and $0 / 1 / 10$-puzzles. Tracing this correspondence through to interlacing triangular arrays using the bijection $\mathscr{T}$, we show that forbidding certain of the $0 / 1 / 10$-puzzle pieces corresponds to forbidding certain patterns in the arrays. In Section 5.2, we prove the key Lemma 5.5 which allows us to split arrays into pairs of arrays of lower rank. Finally, these results are applied in Section 5 to prove Theorems 1.5 to 1.8 .

An extended abstract of part of this work will appear in the proceedings of FPSAC $2025[6]$.

# 2. Preliminaries 

2.1. Interlacing triangular arrays. We now define interlacing triangular arrays, the main objects of study.

Definition 2.1 (Aggarwal-Borodin-Wheeler [1]). An interlacing triangular array $T$ of rank $m$ and height $n$ is a collection $\left\{T_{j, k}^{(i)} \mid 1 \leq i \leq m, 1 \leq j \leq k \leq n\right\}$ of positive integers from $[1, m]$, subject to the following conditions:
(a) For each $k=1, \ldots, n$ we have an equality of multisets:

$$
\left\{T_{j, k}^{(i)} \mid 1 \leq i \leq m, 1 \leq j \leq k\right\}=\left\{1^{k}\right\} \cup \cdots \cup\left\{m^{k}\right\}
$$

(b) Let the horizontal coordinate of $T_{j, k}^{(i)}$ be $h(i, j, k):=i n+j-(n+k) / 2$. If $T_{j, k}^{(i)}=T_{j^{\prime}, k}^{\left(i^{\prime}\right)}=a$ for some $i, j, i^{\prime}, j^{\prime}, k$ with $h(i, j, k)<h\left(i^{\prime}, j^{\prime}, k\right)$, then there must exist $i^{\prime \prime}, j^{\prime \prime}$ with $T_{j^{\prime \prime}, k-1}^{\left(i^{\prime \prime}\right)}=a$ and $h(i, j, k)<h\left(i^{\prime \prime}, j^{\prime \prime}, k-1\right)<h\left(i^{\prime}, j^{\prime}, k\right)$. This entry $T_{j^{\prime \prime}, k-1}^{\left(i^{\prime \prime}\right)}$ is said to interlace with $T_{j, k}^{(i)}$ and $T_{j^{\prime}, k}^{\left(i^{\prime}\right)}$.
For each $k=1, \ldots, n$ we can view $T_{\bullet, k}^{(\bullet)}:=\left\{T_{j, k}^{(i)} \mid 1 \leq i \leq m, 1 \leq j \leq k\right\}$ as the rows of an array of $m$ triangles, from bottom to top. We denote by $\mathcal{T}_{m, n}$ the set of interlacing triangular arrays of rank $m$ and height $n$ and by $\mathcal{T}_{m, n}\left(\lambda^{(1)}, \ldots, \lambda^{(m)}\right)$ the subset whose top row (that is, the row $k=n$ ) consists of $\lambda^{(1)}, \ldots, \lambda^{(m)}$; here $\lambda^{(i)} \in[m]^{n}$ for $i \in[m]$. For $T \in \mathcal{T}_{m, n}$, we use $T^{(i)}$ to denote the $i$-th triangle from left to right, and use $T_{\bullet, k}^{(i)}$ to denote its $k$-th row.

The three triangles in the array have top rows $T_{\bullet, 4}^{(1)}=(1,2,1,3), T_{\bullet, 4}^{(2)}=(1,3,3,2)$, and $T_{\bullet, 4}^{(3)}=(1,2,3,2)$. The same condition holds for other entry values in other pairs of consecutive rows.

Lemma 2.3. Let $T$ be an interlacing triangular array of rank $m$ and height $n$. Then for a fixed $p \in[n], T_{p, k}^{(1)}$ is constant for $p \leq k \leq n$ and $T_{k-p+1, k}^{(m)}$ is constant for $p \leq k \leq n$.

Proof. Let $a=T_{1, n-1}^{(1)}$. By the interlacing condition on $a$ for row $n-1$ and row $n, a$ must appear to the left of $h(1,1, n-1)$, meaning that $T_{1, n}^{(1)}=a$. With the same argument continuing to the right, we can show that $T_{j, n-1}^{(1)}=T_{j, n}^{(1)}$ for all $1 \leq j \leq n-1$. Restricting to the bottom $p$ rows for $p=1, \ldots, n$, with the same argument, we obtain that $T_{p, k}^{(1)}$ is constant for $p \leq k \leq n$. The statement for $T^{(m)}$ is the same, arguing from right to left.
2.2. The partial flag variety. A partial flag $F_{\bullet}$ of dimension $\boldsymbol{d}=\left(0=d_{0} \leq d_{1} \leq\right.$ $\cdots \leq d_{m}=n$ ) is a chain of linear subspaces $0=F_{0} \subset F_{1} \subset \cdots \subset F_{m-1} \subset F_{m}=\mathbb{C}^{n}$ such that $\operatorname{dim} F_{i}=d_{i}$ for $i=1, \ldots, n$. The collection of such flags form the partial flag variety $\mathrm{Fl}(\boldsymbol{d} ; n)$, which admits a Bruhat decomposition into open Schubert cells $\bigsqcup_{w \in S_{n}^{d}} \Omega_{w}$, with the index set

$$
S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}}=\left\{w \in S_{n} \mid \operatorname{Des}(w) \subset\left\{d_{1}, \ldots, d_{m-1}\right\}\right\}
$$

The closure of each open Schubert cell is the Schubert variety $X_{w}=\overline{\Omega_{w}}$. Write $\sigma_{w}:=\left[X_{w}\right] \in H^{2 \ell(w)}(\mathrm{Fl}(\boldsymbol{d} ; n), \mathbb{Z})$ for the Schubert class of $w$, the Poincaré dual to the fundamental class of the Schubert variety $X_{w}$; the Schubert classes $\sigma_{w}$ for $w \in S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}}$ form a basis of $H^{*}(\mathrm{Fl}(\boldsymbol{d} ; n), \mathbb{Z})$. Let $w_{0}^{\boldsymbol{d}}$ be the unique element in $S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}}$ of maximum length, whose Schubert class $\sigma_{w_{0}^{\boldsymbol{d}}}$ is the class of a point. Note that

$$
\ell\left(w_{0}^{\boldsymbol{d}}\right)=\binom{n}{2}-\sum_{i=1}^{m}\binom{d_{i}-d_{i-1}}{2}
$$

Let $S_{\boldsymbol{d}}$ be the parabolic subgroup of $S_{n}$ generated by $\left\{s_{j} \mid j \notin \boldsymbol{d}\right\}$ and let $w_{0}(\boldsymbol{d})$ be the longest element of $S_{\boldsymbol{d}}$. Thus, $S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}}$ is the set of minimum-length coset representatives for $S_{n} / S_{\boldsymbol{d}}$. We have $w_{0}^{\boldsymbol{d}} w_{0}(\boldsymbol{d})=w_{0}$, where $w_{0}=n n-1 \cdots 1$ is the longest permutation in $S_{n}$.

Remark. Readers may be more familiar with the the convention that $\boldsymbol{d}$ is strictly increasing. In our setting, if $d_{i}=d_{i+1}$ for some $i$, then we necessarily have $F_{i}=F_{i+1}$ for $F_{\bullet} \in \mathrm{Fl}(\boldsymbol{d} ; n)$ and thus the geometry remains the same. Our convention that $\boldsymbol{d}$ is only weakly increasing will be convenient in the sequel.

For a sequence of permutations $w^{(1)}, \ldots, w^{(k)} \in S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}}$, the Schubert structure constants $c_{w^{(1)}, \ldots, w^{(k)}}^{w}$ are defined by

$$
\sigma_{w^{(1)}} \cdots \sigma_{w^{(k)}}=\sum_{w \in S_{n}} c_{w^{(1)}, \ldots, w^{(k)}}^{w} \sigma_{w}
$$

The constant $c_{w^{(1)}, \ldots, w^{(k)}}^{w}$ is zero unless $\ell(w)=\ell\left(w^{(1)}\right)+\cdots+\ell\left(w^{(k)}\right)$ and $w \in S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}}$. For a permutation $w \in S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}}$, its dual is $w^{\vee_{\boldsymbol{d}}}:=w_{0} w w_{0}(\boldsymbol{d}) \in S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}}$. By the duality theorem in $H^{*}(\mathrm{Fl}(\boldsymbol{d} ; n))$, for $\ell(u)+\ell(v)=\ell\left(w_{0}^{\boldsymbol{d}}\right)$ we have $\sigma_{u} \sigma_{v}=\delta_{u, v^{\vee} \boldsymbol{d}} \sigma_{w_{0}^{\boldsymbol{d}}}$, where $\delta$ is the Kronecker delta function.

Definition 2.4. Let $\Sigma$ be a finite alphabet with a total order $\left\{q_{1}<\cdots<q_{m}\right\}$. An element $\lambda \in \Sigma^{n}$ is called a Schubert string of size $n$. We say that $\lambda$ has type $q^{\alpha}=q_{1}^{\alpha_{1}} \cdots q_{m}^{\alpha_{k}}$ if $\lambda$ contains $\alpha_{i}$ copies of $q_{i}$, for $i=1, \ldots, m$.

In this paper, we will deal alternately with Schubert strings and with their corresponding permutations that lie in certain parabolic quotients of $S_{n}$.

Definition 2.5. For a Schubert string $\lambda$ of size $n$ and type $q^{\alpha}$, we associate a permutation $w(\lambda)_{\Sigma}=w \in S_{n}$ such that $w\left(d_{i-1}+1\right)<\cdots<w\left(d_{i}\right)$ are the positions of $q_{i}$ 's in $\lambda$, where $\alpha=\alpha(\boldsymbol{d})$ is defined by $\alpha_{1}+\cdots+\alpha_{i}=d_{i}$ for $i=1, \ldots, m$. This map is a bijection from to set of Schubert strings of type $q^{\alpha}$ to $S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}}$. For $w \in S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}}$, write $\lambda(w)_{\Sigma}$ for the corresponding Schubert string. When the alphabet $\Sigma$ and its total order are understood, the subscripts might be omitted.

In the case where the alphabet $\Sigma=\{a, b\}$ has only two letters, two permutations $u, v \in S_{n}^{\{k\}}$ are dual to each other if $\lambda(u)_{a<b}$ can be obtained from $\lambda(v)_{b<a}$ by first reversing the order and then swapping the letters $a$ and $b$.

# 3. From interlacing triangular arrays to puzzles 

The goal of this section is to establish a bijection $\mathscr{T}$ between interlacing triangular arrays of rank 3 and certain edge labelings of $\Delta_{n}$. We call these labelings $1 / 2 / 3$ puzzles since they in turn are in bijection (see Section 5) with the $0 / 1 / 10$-puzzles of Knutson-Tao [12] as generalized by Knutson-Zinn-Justin [15, §4].

# 3.1. $1 / 2 / 3$-Puzzles. We now define $1 / 2 / 3$-puzzles. 

Definition 3.1. We denote by $\Delta_{n}$ the triangular grid graph with side length $n$; see Figure 4. We view $\Delta_{n}$ as embedded in the plane as pictured, allowing us to distinguish between the $\Delta$-oriented and $\nabla$-oriented faces. $$

where the union runs over $\mu$ of type $(m-2)^{n-d_{m-2}} m^{d_{m-2}}$.
Proof. Let $T \in \mathcal{T}_{m, n}\left(\lambda^{(1)}, \ldots, \lambda^{(m)}\right)$ and $(R, S)=\operatorname{split}(T)$. We first argue that $R$ and $S$ are interlacing triangular arrays.

By our assumption on $\boldsymbol{\lambda}$, only the numbers $m, m-1, m-2$ appear in $T^{(1)}$ and $T^{(2)}$. Moreover, $m-1$ appears $k$ times in $T_{\bullet, k}^{(1)} \cup T_{\bullet, k}^{(2)}$ for $k=1, \ldots, n$ since it does not appear in any $T^{(i)}$ with $i>2$. Thus it is easy to see inductively that the number $a_{k}$ from Definition 5.3 is well-defined, that all entries $R_{j, k}^{(3)}$ lie in $\{m-2, m\}$ and that $T_{\bullet, k}^{(1)} \cup T_{\bullet, k}^{(2)} \cup R_{\bullet, k}^{(3)}=\left\{(m-2)^{k},(m-1)^{k}, m^{k}\right\}$ for $k=1, \ldots, n$.

It remains to check the interlacing condition for $R$. The $(m-1)$ 's interlace, because they all appear in $T^{(1)}$ and $T^{(2)}$ and because $T$ is interlacing by hypothesis. Consider the $m$ 's. By the inductive definition of $R^{(3)}$, if $R_{j, k}^{(3)}=m$ for $j \neq 1$, then $R_{j-1, k-1}^{(3)}=m$. Thus between any pair of $m$ 's in $R_{\bullet, k}^{(3)}$ there is an interlacing $m$ in $R_{\bullet, k-1}^{(3)}$, and so the $m$ 's are interlacing within $R^{(3)}$. Furthermore, $a_{k}=m$ if and only if the number of $m$ 's in $T_{\bullet, k}^{(1)} \cup T_{\bullet, k}^{(2)}$ is equal to the number in $T_{\bullet, k-1}^{(1)} \cup T_{\bullet, k-1}^{(2)}$. Thus the $m$ 's alternate between rows $k-1$ and $k$ as we move the horizontal coordinate left to right, and so they interlace. The $(m-2)$ 's are likewise interlacing. An analogous argument show that $S$ is an interlacing triangular array.

Now, define a map merge on

$$
\bigsqcup_{\mu} \mathcal{T}_{3, n}^{\left\{m-2, m-1, m\right\}}\left(\lambda^{(1)}, \lambda^{(2)}, \mu\right) \times \mathcal{T}_{m-1, n}^{[m] \backslash\{m-1\}}\left(\mu^{\dagger}, \lambda^{(3)}, \ldots, \lambda^{(m)}\right)
$$

sending $(R, S) \mapsto\left(R^{(1)}, R^{(2)}, S^{(2)}, S^{(3)}, \ldots, S^{(m-1)}\right)$. It is easy to check that $\operatorname{merge}(R, S)$ lies in $\mathcal{T}_{m, n}\left(\lambda^{(1)}, \ldots, \lambda^{(m)}\right)$ and that merge is the inverse of split.
5.3. Avoiding puzzle pieces. The geometric interpretations of $0 / 1 / 10$-puzzles in terms of Schubert classes in cohomology, the $G_{\xi}$ basis in $K$-theory, and the $G_{\xi}^{*}$ basis in $K$-theory involve forbidding the $\Delta$ - and $\nabla$-oriented $10-10-10$ pieces, or one or the other of these pieces. We call these two pieces, as well as their $1 / 2 / 3$-analogs, the $K$-pieces. In this section, we describe the forbidden substructures in interlacing triangular arrays corresponding to forbidden one or both of the $K$-pieces.

Proposition 5.6. Suppose that $\lambda^{(1)} \in\{2,3\}^{n}, \lambda^{(2)} \in\{1,2,3\}^{n}$, and $\lambda^{(3)} \in\{1,3\}^{n}$. Then the followings are equivalent:
(a) The $0 / 1 / 10$-puzzle $\widetilde{P}$ with boundary conditions $\operatorname{str}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ avoids the piece 1010 .
(b) The $1 / 2 / 3$-puzzle $P$ with boundary conditions $\boldsymbol{\lambda}$ avoids the piece $1_{2}^{3}$.
(c) The array $T=\mathscr{T}(P)$ with top row $\boldsymbol{\lambda}$ avoids 3 and $3_{3}^{2}$ in $T^{(2)}$.
(d) The array $T=\mathscr{T}(P)$ with top row $\boldsymbol{\lambda}$ avoids $2^{3}$ and $1_{3}^{3}$ in $T^{(2)}$.

Proof. Since the piece $1_{2}^{3}$ is sent to the piece $10_{10}^{10}$ by the transformation of Proposition 5.1, the equivalence of (a) and (b) is clear. We now prove the equivalence of (b) and (d).

We use the contrapositive. Suppose that $P$ contains the piece $1_{2}^{3}$ at position $A$. Consider the southeast-to-northwest slice of $P$ containing the piece and the maximal sequence of consecutive $K$-pieces beginning at $A$ and continuing to the northwest within the slice (see diagrams below).
![img-16.jpeg](img-16.jpeg)

This sequence does not continue to the end of the slice because $\lambda^{(1)}$ does not contain 1 by hypothesis. If the last $K$-piece in the sequence is $\nabla$-oriented, then the slice must be as above, left. Thus $T^{(2)}$ contains the bolded instance of $1_{3}^{3}$. If instead the last $K$-piece in the sequence is $\Delta$-oriented, then the slice must be as above, right. In this case $T^{(2)}$ contains the bolded instance of $2^{3}$.

If, conversely, $T^{(2)}$ contains one of the patterns, then $P=\mathscr{T}^{\prime}(T)$ must contain one of the substructures below:

![img-17.jpeg](img-17.jpeg)

In either case, $P$ contains the desired piece.
The equivalence of (b) and (c) can be proven similarly, by considering the slice heading southeast (rather than northwest) from $A$.

The following proposition is closely analogous to Proposition 5.6 and its proof is omitted.

Proposition 5.7. Suppose that $\lambda^{(1)} \in\{2,3\}^{n}, \lambda^{(2)} \in\{1,2,3\}^{n}$, and $\lambda^{(3)} \in\{1,3\}^{n}$. Then the following are equivalent:
(a) The $0 / 1 / 10$-puzzle $\widetilde{P}$ with boundary conditions $\operatorname{str}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ avoids the piece 1010
(b) The $1 / 2 / 3$-puzzle $P$ with boundary conditions $\boldsymbol{\lambda}$ avoids the piece 2
(c) The array $T=\mathscr{T}(P)$ with top row $\boldsymbol{\lambda}$ avoids 1 and 3 in $T^{(2)}$.
(d) The array $T=\mathscr{T}(P)$ with top row $\boldsymbol{\lambda}$ avoids 2 and 3 in $T^{(2)}$.
5.4. Proofs of geometric interpretations. We can now prove Theorems 1.5 to 1.8 .

We first verify the easy cases $m=1$ and 2 . The first is immediate:
Proposition 5.8. For all $n \geq 1$ there is a unique interlacing triangular array in $\mathcal{T}_{1, n}$.

Proof. Clearly we must have $T_{j, k}^{(i)}=1$ for all $i, j, k$, and this is indeed an interlacing triangular array.

Proposition 5.8 corresponds to the fact that, for any of the bases appearing in Theorems 1.5 to 1.8 , the basis element corresponding to the top row $1^{n}$ is the multiplicative identity element of the ring in which it resides.

Proposition 5.9. For each $\lambda \in\{1,2\}^{n}$, there is a unique $T \in \mathcal{T}_{2, n}$ such that $T^{(1)}$ has top row $\lambda$. Furthermore, $T$ satisfies $T^{(2)}=\left(T^{(1)}\right)^{1}$.

Proof. Suppose the result is true for arrays of height $n-1$. And suppose without loss of generality that $\lambda_{1}=1$. Then any such $T$ has $T_{1, k}^{(1)}=1$ for all $k=1, \ldots, n$ and therefore has $T_{k, k}^{(2)}=2$ for all $k$, by Lemma 2.3. Now observe that the remainder $S=\left\{T_{j, k}^{(1)} \mid 2 \leq j \leq k\right\} \cup\left\{T_{j, k}^{(2)} j \leq k-1 \geq 1\right\}$ of the array is in fact an interlacing

triangular array of rank 2 and height $n-1$, with $S^{(1)}$ having top row $\left(\lambda_{2}, \ldots, \lambda_{n}\right)$. The result follows by induction.

For $\lambda \in\{1,2\}^{n}$ we have $\operatorname{str}\left(\left(\lambda, \lambda^{\dagger}\right)\right)=\left(\xi, \xi^{\perp}\right)$ for some $\xi$. Theorems 1.5 to 1.8 hold in the case $m=2$ since $\xi=\left(\xi^{\perp}\right)^{\perp}$ and so $B_{\xi}=1 \cdot B_{\left(\xi^{\perp}\right)^{\perp}}$ for any of the bases appearing in the theorems, agreeing with Proposition 5.9.

We now turn to the proofs for general $m$.
Proof of Theorem 1.5. Let $\xi^{(1)}, \ldots, \xi^{(m)}$ have content $0^{d} 1^{n-d}$, define $\boldsymbol{\lambda}=\operatorname{top}(\boldsymbol{\xi})$, and let $\mathcal{G}_{m, n}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ denote the set of interlacing triangular arrays appearing in the theorem statement. If $m=1$ or 2 , then the theorem holds by the discussion above. Suppose that $m=3$. Then by a result of Vakil [19, Thm. 3.6], $g_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}$ is $(-1)^{d(n-d)-|\boldsymbol{\xi}|}$ times the number of $0 / 1 / 10$-puzzles $\widetilde{P}$ with boundary conditions $\boldsymbol{\xi}$ which avoid the $\nabla$-oriented 10-10-10 piece. By Proposition 5.7, the bijection $\mathscr{T}$ maps the associated $1 / 2 / 3$-puzzles $P$ to interlacing triangular arrays $\mathscr{T}(P)$ with top row $\boldsymbol{\lambda}$ avoiding 1
and $\quad \stackrel{3}{2-3}$ in $T^{(2)}$. The set of these arrays is exactly $\mathcal{G}_{3, n}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$.
Now suppose that $m \geq 4$. By associativity and the definition of $g_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}$ we can write:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\prod_{i=1}^{m-1} G_{\xi^{(i)}} & =\left(G_{\xi^{(1)}} G_{\xi^{(2)}}\right) \prod_{i=3}^{m-1} G_{\xi^{(i)}} \\
& =\sum_{\zeta} g_{\left(\xi^{(1)}, \xi^{(2)}, \zeta\right)} G_{\zeta^{\perp}} \prod_{i=3}^{m-1} G_{\xi^{(i)}} \\
& =\sum_{\zeta, \xi^{(m)}} g_{\left(\xi^{(1)}, \xi^{(2)}, \zeta\right)} g_{\left(\zeta^{\perp}, \xi^{(3)}, \ldots, \xi^{(m)}\right)} G_{\left(\xi^{(m)}\right)^{\perp}} .
\end{aligned}
$$

By induction on $m$, both $g_{\left(\xi^{(1)}, \xi^{(2)}, \zeta\right)}$ and $g_{\left(\zeta^{\perp}, \xi^{(3)}, \ldots, \xi^{(m)}\right)}$ are the (signed) sizes of the corresponding sets $\mathcal{G}_{3, n}\left(\hat{\lambda}^{(1)}, \hat{\lambda}^{(2)}, \mu\right)$ and $\mathcal{G}_{m-1, n}\left(\mu^{\dagger}, \hat{\lambda}^{(3)}, \ldots, \hat{\lambda}^{(m)}\right)$ of arrays, where $\mu$ is defined by $\operatorname{top}\left(\xi^{(1)}, \xi^{(2)}, \zeta\right)=\left(\hat{\lambda}^{(1)}, \hat{\lambda}^{(2)}, \mu\right)$ and where $\operatorname{top}\left(\zeta^{\perp}, \xi^{(3)}, \ldots, \xi^{(m)}\right)=$ $\left(\mu^{\dagger}, \hat{\lambda}^{(3)}, \ldots, \hat{\lambda}^{(m)}\right)$.

Consider the restriction of the splitting map split (see Lemma 5.5) from $\mathcal{T}_{m, n}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ to $\mathcal{G}_{m, n}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$. For $T \in \mathcal{G}_{m, n}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ and $(R, S)=\operatorname{split}(T)$, it is clear by construction that $R$ and $S$ also avoid the patterns from (2), with indices shifted to match the supports of $R$ and $S$. Likewise, merge sends pairs of arrays avoiding these patterns to arrays avoiding the patterns. Note that for each $\zeta$, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left(d(n-d)-\left|\left(\xi^{(1)}, \xi^{(2)}, \zeta\right)\right|\right) & +\left(d(n-d)-\left|\left(\zeta^{\perp}, \xi^{(3)}, \ldots, \xi^{(m)}\right)\right|\right) \\
& =2 d(n-d)-\left(|\zeta|+\left|\zeta^{\perp}\right|\right)-|\boldsymbol{\xi}| \\
& =d(n-d)-|\boldsymbol{\xi}| .
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus, applying merge to the support-shifted sets of arrays from the previous paragraph, we conclude that $g_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}$ is $(-1)^{d(n-d)-|\boldsymbol{\xi}|}$ times $\left|\mathcal{G}_{m, n}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})\right|$.

Proof of Theorem 1.6. The proof is very similar to the proof of Theorem 1.5. Let $\mathcal{G}_{m, n}^{*}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ denote the set of interlacing triangular arrays appearing in the statement of Theorem 1.6. The cases $m=1$ and 2 are again covered by Propositions 5.8 and 5.9. For $m=3$, we instead use a result [20, Thm. 1' \& Rmk. 2] of Wheeler-ZinnJustin, which implies that $g_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}^{*}$ is $(-1)^{d(n-d)-|\boldsymbol{\xi}|}$ times the number of $0 / 1 / 10$-puzzles $\widehat{P}$ with boundary conditions $\boldsymbol{\xi}$ which avoid instead the $\Delta$-oriented $10-10-10$ piece. By Proposition 5.6, the bijection $\mathscr{T}$ maps the associated $1 / 2 / 3$-puzzles $P$ to interlacing triangular arrays $\mathscr{T}(P)$ with top row $\boldsymbol{\lambda}$ avoiding $\begin{array}{ll}3 & \text { and } \\ 1 & 3\end{array} \quad \begin{array}{ll}3-2 & \text { in } T^{(2)} .\end{array}$ The set of these arrays is exactly $\mathcal{G}_{3, n}^{*}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$. We can prove the cases $m \geq 4$ using Lemma 5.5 as we did in the proof of Theorem 1.5.

Proof of Theorem 1.7. We again use the same proof strategy, although some care is now required to properly account for the different partial flag varieties involved. Let $\boldsymbol{d}, \boldsymbol{\lambda}$, and $\boldsymbol{w}$ be as in the theorem statement and define $\boldsymbol{d}^{\prime}=\left(d_{m-2} \leq d_{m-1}\right)$ and $\boldsymbol{d}^{\prime \prime}=\left(d_{1} \leq \cdots \leq d_{m-2}\right)$. Let $\mathcal{S}_{m, n}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ denote the set of interlacing triangular arrays from the theorem.

For $m=3$, the set $\mathcal{S}_{3, n}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ is in bijection with $0 / 1 / 10$-puzzles avoiding both the $\Delta$ and $\nabla$-oriented 10-10-10 pieces by Propositions 5.6 and 5.7. According to the theorem statement, $\lambda^{(1)}, \lambda^{(2)}, \lambda^{(3)}$ have contents $2^{d_{2}} 3^{n-d_{2}}, 1^{d_{1}} 2^{n-d_{2}} 3^{d_{2}-d_{1}}$, and $1^{n-d_{1}} 3^{d_{1}}$, respectively. Thus, by Proposition 5.1, the corresponding $0 / 1 / 10$-puzzles have left, right, and bottom boundary conditions $\xi^{(1)}=0^{d_{2}} 1^{n-d_{2}}, \xi^{(2)}=0^{d_{1}}(01)^{d_{2}-d_{1}} 1^{n-d_{2}}$, and $\xi^{(3)}=0^{d_{1}} 1^{n-d_{1}}$, respectively.

By work of Halacheva-Knutson-Zinn-Justin [10, Thm. 2], 0/1/10-puzzles with no 10-10-10 pieces and left, right, and bottom boundary conditions $\xi^{(3)}, \xi^{(1)}$, and $\xi^{(2)}$ (notice the rotated indices!) compute structure constants for multiplying inside $H^{*}\left(\mathrm{Fl}\left(d_{1}, d_{2} ; n\right)\right)$ classes pulled back (under the natural projections $\mathrm{Fl}\left(d_{1}, d_{2} ; n\right) \rightarrow$ $\operatorname{Gr}\left(d_{i} ; n\right)$ for $\left.i=1,2\right)$ from $\operatorname{Gr}\left(d_{1}, n\right)$ and $\operatorname{Gr}\left(d_{2}, n\right)$. Since the set of allowed puzzle pieces is closed under $120^{\circ}$-rotation, and since this maps our boundary conditions to those of [10], this rotation gives a bijection between their puzzles and ours. In Theorem 1.7, we are considering the coefficient of (the dual of) a class pulled back from $\operatorname{Gr}\left(d_{1}, n\right)$ in the product of a class pulled back from $\operatorname{Gr}\left(d_{2}, n\right)$ and a Schubert class from $\mathrm{Fl}\left(d_{1}, d_{2} ; n\right)$. Both of these geometric quantities can be expressed as the same product of three classes in $H^{*}\left(\mathrm{Fl}\left(d_{1}, d_{2} ; n\right)\right)$ in different orders, so they agree. Thus we have that, for $m=3$, the cardinality of the set $\mathcal{S}_{3, n}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ computes the desired structure constant $c_{\boldsymbol{w}}$. This result implies in particular that if $\mathcal{S}_{3, n}(\boldsymbol{\lambda})$ is nonempty, then $\ell\left(w^{(1)}\right)+\ell\left(w^{(2)}\right)+\ell\left(w^{(3)}\right)=\ell\left(w_{0}^{\boldsymbol{d}}\right)=\operatorname{dim}_{\mathbb{C}}(\operatorname{Fl}(\boldsymbol{d} ; n))$ (in terms of puzzles, this also follows from [14, Lem. 2.3]).

Now suppose $m \geq 4$. We will again apply Lemma 5.5; the split and merge maps are again easily seen to respect the top row conditions and the avoided patterns. We need to check that the corresponding recurrence holds on the geometric side.

Suppose that $c_{w}$ is nonzero, so $\sum_{i} \ell\left(w^{(i)}\right)=\operatorname{dim}_{\mathbb{C}} \mathrm{Fl}(\boldsymbol{d} ; n)$. Then we have

$$
\prod_{i=1}^{m} \sigma_{w^{(i)}}=\sum_{u, v} c_{w^{(1)}, w^{(2)}}^{u} c_{w^{(3)}, \ldots, w^{(m)}}^{v} \sigma_{u} \sigma_{v}
$$

where the sum runs over $u \in S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}^{\prime}}$ and $v \in S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}^{\prime \prime}}$ such that $\ell(u)+\ell(v)=\operatorname{dim}_{\mathbb{C}} \operatorname{Fl}(\boldsymbol{d} ; n)$. The product of two such Schubert classes is zero unless $v=u^{\vee \boldsymbol{d}}$, so suppose we are in this case. We claim then that $u^{\vee \boldsymbol{d}^{\prime}}$ and $v^{\vee \boldsymbol{d}^{\prime \prime}}$ in fact lie in $S_{n}^{\left\{d_{m-2}\right\}}$. We prove the first claim, the second being similar. If $d_{m-2}=d_{m-1}$, then $S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}^{\prime}}=S_{n}^{\left\{d_{m-2}\right\}}$, so we are done. So suppose $d_{m-2}<d_{m-1}$. We know that $u^{\vee \boldsymbol{d}}=v \in S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}^{\prime \prime}}$ has no descent at $d_{m-1}$. But $u^{\vee \boldsymbol{d}}=w_{0} u w_{0}(\boldsymbol{d})$ and $u^{\vee \boldsymbol{d}^{\prime}}=w_{0} u w_{0}\left(\boldsymbol{d}^{\prime}\right)$ differ by a permutation on $1,2, \ldots, d_{m-2}$, so the same is true of $u^{\vee \boldsymbol{d}^{\prime}}$. Thus $u^{\vee \boldsymbol{d}^{\prime}} \in S_{n}^{\boldsymbol{d}^{\prime} \backslash\left\{d_{m-1}\right\}}=S_{n}^{\left\{d_{m-2}\right\}}$. Therefore the nonzero summands in (5) contain (duals of) classes pulled back from $\operatorname{Gr}\left(d_{m-2}, n\right)$; this corresponds exactly to the conditions on the top row $\mu$ of the arrays in (4), so the result follows by induction.

Proof of Theorem 1.8. The proof again takes the same form as those of Theorems 1.5 and 1.6. Now, for the $m=3$ case we use a result [15, Thm. 5.4] of Knutson-ZinnJustin which implies that $(-1)^{d(n-d)-\left|\xi\right|} s_{\boldsymbol{\xi}}$ is the number of $0 / 1 / 10$-puzzles $\widetilde{P}$ with boundary conditions $\boldsymbol{\xi}$, now allowing all of the puzzle pieces. These are in bijection with the desired interlacing triangular arrays by Proposition 5.1 and Theorem 3.5. Lemma 5.5 can again be applied to prove the cases $m \geq 4$.

abstract:
We show that interlacing triangular arrays, introduced by
Aggarwal-Borodin-Wheeler to study certain probability measures, can be used to
compute structure constants for multiplying Schubert classes in the $K$-theory
of Grassmannians, in the cohomology of their cotangent bundles, and in the
cohomology of partial flag varieties. Our results are achieved by establishing
a splitting lemma, allowing for interlacing triangular arrays of high rank to
be decomposed into arrays of lower rank, and by constructing a bijection
between interlacing triangular arrays of rank 3 with certain proper vertex
colorings of the triangular grid graph that factors through generalizations of
Knutson-Tao puzzles. Along the way, we prove one enumerative conjecture of
Aggarwal-Borodin-Wheeler and disprove another.
